<h3 id="logistic_regr_fitself-x-y"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">logistic_regr_fit(self, X, y):</code></h3>

<p>This method fits input values with output values. Firstly it calls the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">add_intercept</code> method for $X$ and initalises all $\theta_ i$ to 0.</p>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">theta</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">])</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>It then loops <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">self.n</code> times (number of iterations) calls some methods. Firstly it calls the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">logistic_regr_hypothesis(self, X, theta)</code> method to calculate some intial hypothesis values based on the $\theta_ i$. It then calculates the gradient of the lossusing a derivative of the loss function (See equation below) and updates theta using this gradient and the learning rate.</p>

<p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/429/1*gobKgGbRWDAoVFAan_HjxQ.png" alt="Derivative of the loss function" /></p>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">theta</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">theta</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">grad</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">lr</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>It calcuates the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">loss_cross_entropy</code> and then stores this. After the loop it returns final $\theta_ i$ values and the loss for each iteration.</p>

<h3 id="predict_probabilitiesself-x"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">predict_probabilities(self, X):</code></h3>

<p>This predicts outputs based on a set of inputs using the trained model. It returns a list of probablities between 0 and 1.</p>

<h3 id="predict_classself"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">predict_class(self)</code></h3>

<p>This final method simply rounds the the above output so as to return the predicted class. In this binary classifier values will be either 0 or 1.</p>

